Getting into the nimzo-indian here.
I play a3 in an attempt to trap the bishop. A possible line here is 4. a3 Ba5  5. b4 Bb6 and finally, c5 traps the bishop

Black plays along along a variation of the nimzo-indian. I personally like to see a move like this early in a game trading a bishop for a knight in a game that in most cases turns out to be fairly open where bishops have a slight advantage over knights...

Still in opening book theory, I was actually surprised to see this move. Most players are not that schooled this deep in the Nimzo-indian (Samisch Variation). In fact, I have no idea what the response from white is supposed to be here.
